<TITLE> RAB links militants to Aug 21 attack on Hasina </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 29 (bdnews24.com) - The Rapid Action Battalion has arrested nine people with suspected ties to banned Islamist outfit Harkat-ul-Jihad in separate raids in different areas of the country, officers said Monday. Some of the arrestees admitted to involvement in the August 21, 2004 grenade attack on Awami League president Sheikh Hasina on Bangabandhu Avenue, RAB media and legal affairs wing chief AK Azad told bdnews24.com. The elite force also seized two Chinese rifles, two revolvers, 16 grenades and a large quantity of bomb-making materials. RAB arrested Hosain Ahmed in Narsingdi, Ali Ahmed in Jhenidah and Baki Billah in Magura. The six others are Abul Kalam Azad, Jahangir Alam, Abdul Quddus, Omar Faruque, Amirul Islam and Mokaddes Billah, arrested in undisclosed locations. The RAB operations, based on intelligence obtained from detained Harkat-ul-Jihad leader Mufti Hannan, were conducted Sunday night through early Monday in different parts of the country, Azad said. The deadly Aug 21 attack on a rally of the then opposition Awami League, where Hasina spoke, killed 22 people. Hasina who had escaped major injuries was bundled into her bulletproof car and rushed away. bdnews24.com/br
